Citi Bike

2022-04-20

Domain knowledge (1.1)

Citi Bike is a New York City’s bike share system. They are the biggest bike sharing in US. Their main focus is not just to offer an easy and cheap service to transport users from point A to B; Citi Bike offers a transportation system that helps the environment, the local community and the users themselves.

A green alternative to other urban means of transportation.

HOW DOES IT WORK?

Citi Bike works in 4 steps:

  • Join : by downloading the mobile phone app and subscribing to the service at a price of $15 per month, $15 for a day pass or $3.99 for a single time trip.
  • Unlock ; once your account is settled you need only to find a bike nearby and ride on.
  • Ride : the city is yours, take as many short rides as you need! (but keep it within 30 minutes if you are not a subscriber)
  • Return : when you reach your destination, return the bike to one of the many Citi Bike’s stations around the city and secure it in there.

HOW SUCCESSFUL ARE THEY ?

Citi Bike started in 2013 with 5000 subscribers and 6000 bikes throughout hundreds of stations in Manhattan and Brooklyn. In the next 8 years they didn’t grow just in numbers (more than 150,000 subscribers and 100,000,000 trips by July 2020), they have become a part of New York:

In 2013 by pedalling, Citi Bike users powered the Times Square New Year’s Eve Ball and in June of the same year they were on the cover page of The New Yorker.

Citi Bike are enjoyed a stunning success, they offer a cheaper and greener service for quick trips around town, promising an agile mean of transportation in a cluttered city like New York.

Data types (1.5)

After the cleaning of the raw data set, the data frame I am going to work on is composed of these variable and types:

  • bike_id, , ID of the bike hired

  • start_time <S3: POSIXct>, time the bike was hired

  • stop_time <S3: POSIXct>, time the bike was returned

  • rent_length_minutes , the total in minutes that the bike was lent

  • start_station , where the bike was taken

  • end_station , where it was returned

  • start_lat , latitude where it was taken

  • start_long , longitude where it was taken

  • end_lat , latitude where it was returned

  • end_long , longitude where it was returned

  • user_type , user type, subscriber or a one-time user

  • user_age , the user age

  • birth_year , the user birth year

  • gender , users’ the user gender

  • hire_year , a column useful for calculating bike hire by year

  • hire_month , a column useful for calculating bike hire by month

  • hire_day , a column useful for calculating bike hire by day

Data quality and data bias (1.6)

The dataset is not dramatically messy, it didn’t require any major cleaning. I have noticed a couple of small out of scale values (133 old person riding a bike?). Another off value is the close to two-hundred 49 years old occasional Citi Bike users. This is way off the average number of other occasional users divided by age we see in the data set. I’ve decided to not exclude this from the analysis; unlike the ultra-centenary bikers although odd (very, very odd) this doesn’t look like a mistake made while collecting data.

Preparing data for visualisation (1.7)

As said above, the data doesn’t need any major cleaning.

Belove my process of data cleaning:

Libraries for the cleaning process:

library(tsibbledata)
library(lubridate)
library(sf)
library(leaflet)
library(tidyverse)

Storing the data in a new variable.

ncy_bikes_df <- nyc_bikes

Creating a new column rent_length, using the lubridate function as.period() to generate a value for the length of the time a bike was rented. Then changing it in a numeric value and specify they are minutes. Relocating this new column after stop_time.

ncy_bikes_df <- ncy_bikes_df %>% 
  mutate(rent_lengt_minutes = as.period(stop_time - start_time),
         rent_lengt_minutes = as.numeric(rent_lengt_minutes, "minutes")) %>%  
  relocate(rent_lengt_minutes, .after = stop_time)

Creating a new column each for year, month and day. I know this looks messy, and it is, but it will make my life easier when plotting. It will be useful to have them during the analysis to check the number of hires by day, month and year.

ncy_bikes_df <- ncy_bikes_df %>% 
  mutate(
    hire_year = year(start_time),
    hire_month = month(start_time, label = TRUE),
    hire_day = wday(start_time, label = TRUE))

Relocating and renaming a couple of columns: end_station after start_station, easy to read this way. Renaming type in user_type so it’s clearer that is referring to the type of subscription.

ncy_bikes_df <- ncy_bikes_df %>% 
  relocate(end_station, .after = start_station) %>% 
  rename(user_type = type)

Creating a new column with the age of the users, more useful when it will come to plotting than a birth date.

ncy_bikes_df <- ncy_bikes_df %>% 
  mutate(user_age = as.numeric(hire_year - birth_year)) %>% 
  relocate(user_age, .after = user_type)

Writing the .csv file at the end.

3. Data visualisation

In this analysis I would like to discuss Citi Bike subscription method.

At the moment users have three choices:

  • $15 per month annual membership.

  • $3.99 single trip up to 30 minutes.

  • $15 day pass.

I will analyse relations and differences between users with a subscription (Subscribers from now on) and occasional users (Customers from now on).

  • Do they use the service for different purposes?

  • Do they have any characteristic in common?

  • Is there a way to attract Customers to a subscription plan?

  • Does Citi Bike needs a new membership option, like a trimester subscription plan?

Customers and Subscribers in numbers

Most of the bikes in this data set are used by Subscribers. Users in the annual plan make almost 4000 thousand bike trips, against short to 300 that Customer make. Now that we have established the numbers, let’s move on analyse the two categories.

What weekday is the most popular for hiring a bike?

The numbers are constant during working days, we can see a small pick on Tuesdays. No surprising, most of the users are Subscribers, the Customers numbers are minimal compared to regular users. On the weekend there’s an obvious drop in the numbers but we can see a first interesting difference between the two categories:

Unlike Subscribers, there’s a small peak in Customers numbers. This hints to the main difference between the two categories, people with a Citi Bike subscription are most probably commuter, while Customer users are most probably leisure bikers, looking for a stroll in town during the weekend.

Let’s explore this more in the next visual.

Average hire length

hire_lenght <- bikes_data %>% 
  arrange(desc(rent_lengt_minutes))

hire_lenght_filtred <- hire_lenght %>% 
  filter(rent_lengt_minutes < 700.00000) # In two occasion users have rented bikes for three days. Beside this being against the policy of short lent of Citi Bike I have the feeling this could be a mistake, I don't want the total mean to be pulled by these values so I am going to filter out any bike hire longer than 700 minutes.  

avg_run <- hire_lenght_filtred %>% 
  group_by(user_type) %>% 
  summarise(avg_run = mean(rent_lengt_minutes, na.rm = TRUE))
avg_hire_time_users <-  ggplot(avg_run) +
  geom_col(aes(x = user_type, y = avg_run, fill = user_type)) +
  scale_fill_manual("Type of User", values = c("Customer" = "#eb1c24", 
                                 "Subscriber" = "#005dab")) +
  ggtitle("Customer avg hire length vs Subscribers") +
  labs(x = "Type of User", y = "Average bike hire lenght") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(text=element_text(size=16,  family = "Mary Ann"))

A clear difference again, Customers ride their bikes in average far more time than Subscribers do. They use in fully the $3.99 worth half an hour on a classic cycle that Citi Bike offers. From this data, is unlike that a Customer will use Citi Bike for a short commute in town rather than jump on Uber for example.

Conclusions

To answer the questions at the beginning of the analysis:

  • Do Subscribers and Customer use the service for different purpose?

Yes, the data suggest that a user with a subscription is more likely to use Citi Bike for short commuting on a daily base during working days. On the other hand a Customer would use Citi Bike mostly for leisure, on a weekend on a summer month riding longer in average than a Subscriber.

  • Do they have any characteristic in common?

Not really, Subscribers show an age pattern while Customer don’t, they have a small increase to the same age range (25 to 35) where Subscribers peak but this is barely noticeable. Their average hire length is totally different.

  • Is there a way to attract Customers to a subscription plan?

Before starting this analysis I would have believed that many Customers were drove away by the one year subscription plan, not wanting to commit this long especially having in mind winter months. Now after looking at the two categories I can’t say this to be true. They are two different categories with two different needs

  • Does Citi Bike need a new membership option, like a trimester subscription plan?

Not necessarily. I’d suggest a trail on a trimester subscription plan for summer month or a weekend plan, in particular aimed to the 25-35 age group. Anyhow there’s no suggestion in the data that this will translate in an increase in subscriptions.
